Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Sywell, Northamptonshire, Olde England":"Sywell, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Harrowden, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrowden, Northamptonshire, England","Wolfage, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tresham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Tresham in Hawkesbury (Gloucs)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Tresham was born in 1404, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Thomas Tresham, was 44 and his mother, Filia Rempston, was 44. He married Lady Isabelle Vaux in 1434, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. In 1439, at the age of 35, his occupation is listed as speaker of the house of commons. He died on 22 September 1450, in Harrowden, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 46, and was buried in Harrowden, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1404–22 September 1450":"1404–22. september 1450","1404–1450":"1404–1450","1404–1478":"1404–1478","1420